Building a Full Stack Web App with Flask
Tutorial

Building a Full Stack Web App with Flask

11 steps

We will go through developing a dynamic web application with the Python web micro-framework, Flask, by introducing models and controllers into the web application. Players will learn how to integrate models and controllers to implement CRUD operations into the Flask application that they created previously.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

Creating routes with Flask

Learning Outcomes

By the end of your learning, you will be able to:

  • Implement authentication with Flask
  • Integrate SQLAlchemy with Flask
  • Deploy a complete Flask application

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 11

  • Step 1: Application Brief

    We will be developing a more complete project where we will integrate an SQLite database to provide dynamic content on our web application and provide the fundamental blocks for our authentication features.

    SQLite databases are stored as single files on disk, which makes them highly portable and manageable. They are widely used in various applications, especially for applications that do not require large-scale data processing. It provides a simple and efficient way to store and retrieve structured data, making it a popular choice for many developers.

    We will use SQLAlchemy to carry out Create, Read, Update and Delete (CRUD) operations on the database to present a list of products and add a layer of authentication using Flask. SQLAlchemy is a powerful Python library that facilitates interaction with databases by abstracting database management complexities. It enables users to create, manage, and query databases using Python code, allowing for seamless integration between the code and the underlying database system.

    For this project, create new folders and files with the following file structure.

    • Firstly, create a Quest3 folder
    • Within the Quest3 folder, create 1 file named requirements.txt, and one folder named app
    • Within the app folder, you will need to create 3 subfolders controllers, static and templates
    • Within the app folder, create 2 files app.py and models.py
    • Within the controllers folder, create two files products.py and users.py
    • Within the static folder, create a file style.css
    • Within the templates folder, create a file index.html

    You may refer to the image below for the folder structure.

    Similar to what we did previously, we created the static and templates folder to store our HTML and CSS files. In your terminal, run the following command in the Quest3 directory to create your virtual environment.

    python3 -m venv ./venv/

    To initialise your virtual environment, you will need to enter the following command in your terminal. 

    Windows users: .\venv\Scripts\activate.bat

    MacOS and Linux Users: source ./venv/bin/activate

    Here, we have an additional models.py file to store our database objects for SQLAlchemy to use, and the controllers folder to define our helper functions that carry out the CRUD operations.

    As we will be using SQLAlchemy, we need to install more dependencies or packages.

    Once done, you should see the message 'Successfully installed Flask-3.0.3 Flask-SQLAlchemy-3.1.1 Jinja2-3.1.4 MarkupSafe-2.1.5 Werkzeug-3.0.3 blinker-1.8.2 click-8.1.7 flask-login-0.6.3 greenlet-3.0.3 itsdangerous-2.2.0 sqlalchemy-2.0.30 typing-extensions-4.12.2'.

  • Step 3: Creating the Models

    Now, we want to create some classes that SQLAlchemy can use to help us with querying and managing our database. For this project, we will create 2 classes, one for products, and another for users.

    In models.py, paste the code below.

    from flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy
from flask_login import UserMixin

db = SQLAlchemy()

class Product(db.Model):
    id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key = True)
    title = db.Column(db.String(50), nullable = False)
    description = db.Column(db.String(100), nullable = False)
    price = db.Column(db.Float, nullable = False)
    category = db.Column(db.String(50), nullable = False)
    image = db.Column(db.String(50), nullable = False)
   
class User(db.Model, UserMixin):
    id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key = True)
    username = db.Column(db.String(50), nullable = False)
    password = db.Column(db.String(100), nullable = False)
    email = db.Column(db.String(50), nullable = False)
    role = db.Column(db.String(50), nullable = False)
    Python

    The code creates the Product class with some standard attributes such as the products title and description, and the User class with attributes we will need later on for authentication.

  • Step 4: Creating the Controllers

    For our application to execute CRUD operations on the database, we should first define some reusable helper functions that we could use later.

    In products.py, paste the code below.

    from models import Product, db
from sqlalchemy import exc

def get_products():
    products = Product.query.all()
    return products

def get_product(id):
    product = Product.query.get(id)
    return product

def add_product(title, description, price, category, image):
    try:
        new_product = Product(
            title = title,
            description = description,
            price = price,
            category = category,
            image = image
        )
        db.session.add(new_product)
        db.session.commit()
        return True
    except exc.IntegrityError:
        db.session.rollback()
        return False
   
def update_product(id, title, description, price, category, image):
    try:
        product = Product.query.get(id)
        product.title = title
        product.description = description
        product.price = price
        product.category = category
        product.image = image
        db.session.commit()
        return True
    except exc.IntegrityError:
        db.session.rollback()
        return False
   
def delete_product(id):
    try:
        product = Product.query.get(id)
        db.session.delete(product)
        db.session.commit()
        return True
    except exc.IntegrityError:
        db.session.rollback()
        return False
    Python

    In this file, we are importing the necessary packages and defining functions that assist us with the following:

    • Getting all products
    • Getting a product by its ID
    • Adding a product
    • Updating a product by its ID
    • Deleting a product by its ID

    Next, open users.py and paste the code below.

    from models import User, db
from sqlalchemy import exc

def get_users():
    users = User.query.all()
    return users

def get_user(id):
    user = User.query.get(id)
    return user

def add_user(username, password, email, role):
    try:
        new_user = User(
            username = username,
            password = password,
            email = email,
            role = role
        )
        db.session.add(new_user)
        db.session.commit()
        return True
    except exc.IntegrityError:
        db.session.rollback()
        return False
   
def update_user(id, username, password, email, role):
    try:
        user = User.query.get(id)
        user.username = username
        user.password = password
        user.email = email
        user.role = role
        db.session.commit()
        return True
    except exc.IntegrityError:
        db.session.rollback()
        return False
   
def delete_user(id):
    try:
        user = User.query.get(id)
        db.session.delete(user)
        db.session.commit()
        return True
    except exc.IntegrityError:
        db.session.rollback()
        return False
   
def get_user_by_username(username):
    user = User.query.filter_by(username = username).first()
    return user
    Python

    Similar to products.py, we are creating functions to help us create, read, update and delete user objects.

  • Step 7: Putting Everything Together, Part 1

    Now that you have your pages set up, let's put your front end, back end and database together into app.py. Follow the instructions carefully and append the code snippets to app.py to get your website working!

    Firstly, import the libraries that we will use, including Flask, sqlalchemy, and the models and controllers we created earlier.

    from flask import Flask, request, render_template, redirect, url_for
from models import Product, User, db
from controllers.users import get_users, get_user, add_user, update_user, delete_user, get_user_by_username
from controllers.products import get_products, get_product, add_product, update_product, delete_product
from sqlalchemy import exc
import hashlib
from flask_login import LoginManager, login_user, current_user, logout_user, login_required
from werkzeug.utils import secure_filename
import secrets
    Python

    Next, create the Flask application, attach the database and login manager, and set some configurations.

    app = Flask(__name__, template_folder = 'templates', static_folder = 'static')
app.config['SECRET_KEY'] = secrets.token_hex(16)
app.config['SQLALCHEMY_DATABASE_URI'] = 'sqlite:///database.db'
db.init_app(app)

login_manager = LoginManager()
login_manager.login_view = 'login'
login_manager.init_app(app)

@login_manager.user_loader
def load_user(user_id):
    # since the user_id is just the primary key of our user table, use it in the query for the user
    return User.query.get(int(user_id))
    Python

    Now, add this code snippet to insert the data into the tables in the database. This code iterates through the arrays we initialised earlier and individually inserts them into the database using SQLAlchemy.

    with app.app_context():
    db.create_all()
    try:
        for product in products:
            new_product = Product(
                id = product['id'],
                title = product['title'],
                description = product['description'],
                price = product['price'],
                category = product['category'],
                image = product['image']
            )
            db.session.add(new_product)
        db.session.commit()

    except exc.IntegrityError:
        db.session.rollback()
        print('Products already exist in database')

    try:
        for user in users:
            new_user = User(
                id = user['id'],
                username = user['username'],
                password = user['password'],
                email = user['email'],
                role = user['role']
            )
            db.session.add(new_user)
        db.session.commit()

    except exc.IntegrityError:
        db.session.rollback()
        print('Users already exist in database')
    Python

  • Step 8: Putting Everything Together, Part 2 - Product Routes

    In this step, we will be creating the routes or endpoints that users can navigate to on their browsers. We will continue to add code to our app.py file.

    First, the / endpoint, the index or main page, will render the contents of index.html with the shop name, list of products, and current user data.

    @app.route('/')
def index():
    return render_template('index.html', shopname = shopname, products = get_products(),user = current_user)
    Python

    The /product/<int:id> endpoint will display an update form with the details of the product with the corresponding product ID. This would look something like /product/1.

    @app.route('/product/<int:id>')
def product(id):
    return render_template('product.html', shopname = shopname, product = get_product(id),user = current_user)
    Python

    Next is the /product/update/<int:id> endpoint, which uses the POST method to retrieve form data to update the product. The @login_required decorator adds a middleware for the endpoint, which checks that a user is authenticated and allowed to access the endpoint, before moving on to the actual code in the function.

    @app.route('/product/update/<int:id>', methods = ['POST'])
@login_required
def update(id):
    title = request.form['title']
    description = request.form['description']
    price = request.form['price']
    category = request.form['category']
    image = request.form['image']
    if update_product(id, title, description, price, category, image):
        return redirect(url_for('index'))
    else:
        return redirect(url_for('product', id = id, error = "Unable to update product"))
    Python

    Then, add the /product/add endpoint with both GET and POST methods. When the user browses to /product/add, they will be shown add.html. If they make a POST request, the function retrieves the product information and saves it into the database.

    @app.route('/product/add', methods = ['GET', 'POST'])
@login_required
def add():
    if request.method == 'POST':
        title = request.form['title']
        description = request.form['description']
        price = request.form['price']
        category = request.form['category']
        image = request.files['image']
        image_filename = secure_filename(image.filename)
        image.save('static/' + image_filename)
        if add_product(title, description, price, category, image_filename):
            return redirect(url_for('index'))
        else:
            return redirect(url_for('index', error = "Unable to add product"))
    else:
        return render_template('add.html', shopname = shopname, user = current_user)
    Python

    And the last product API route will be the /product/delete/<int:id> route which deletes the product from the database based on the specified ID.

    @app.route('/product/delete/<int:id>', methods = ['GET'])
@login_required
def delete(id):
    if delete_product(id):
        return redirect(url_for('index'))
    else:
        return redirect(url_for('index', error = "Unable to delete product"))
    Python
  • Step 9: Putting Everything Together, Part 3 - User Routes

    Now, we have to add authentication routes in app.py.

    Firstly, add the /login route which renders login.html on a GET request, and performs authentication on the username and password submitted in a POST request.

    @app.route('/login', methods = ['GET', 'POST'])
def login():
    if request.method == 'POST':
        username = request.form['username']
        password = request.form['password']
        user = get_user_by_username(username)

        hashed_password = hashlib.sha256(password.encode()).hexdigest()

        if user and user.password == hashed_password:
            login_user(user, remember=True)
            return redirect(url_for('index'))
        else:
            return redirect(url_for('login', error = "Invalid username or password"))
    else:
        return render_template('login.html', shopname = shopname, user = current_user, error = request.args.get('error'))
    Python

    Then, add the /register route to allow users to create accounts. On a GET request, users should be shown register.html, while on a POST request, their information should be saved into the database.

    @app.route('/register', methods = ['GET', 'POST'])
def register():
    if request.method == 'POST':
        username = request.form['username']
        password = request.form['password']
        email = request.form['email']
   
        hashed_password = hashlib.sha256(password.encode()).hexdigest()
       
        if add_user(username, hashed_password, email, 'user'):
            return redirect(url_for('login'))
        else:
            return redirect(url_for('register', error = "Unable to register user"))
    else:
        return render_template('register.html', shopname = shopname, user = current_user, error = request.args.get('error'))
    Python

    And lastly, the /logout route for users to logout.

    @app.route('/logout')
def logout():
    logout_user()
    return redirect(url_for('login'))
    Python

    Finally, for the code to run, add the following line to the bottom of the file.

    if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug = True)
